@node Over "Overview"

@{b}OVERVIEW------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

This is an implementation of the Tunnels & Trolls game (5th Edition), in
its solitaire form, consisting of the game engine and 32 adventures. It
allows you to play the adventures without pen, paper, dice, cards, nor the
adventures themselves. The complete T&T rulebook will prove handy but is
not essential.
  The included adventures are:

    * Abyss (1980)
    * Amulet of the Salkti (1984)
    * Arena of Khazan (1979)
    * Beyond the Silvered Pane (1978)
    * Beyond the Wall of Tears (1984)
    * Blue Frog Tavern (1981)
    * Buffalo Castle (1976)
    * Captif d'Yvoire (1984)
    * Caravan to Tiern (1989)
    * Circle of Ice (1980)
    * City of Terrors (1978)
    * Dargon's Dungeon (1977)
    * Dark Temple (1991)
    * Deathtrap Equalizer (1977)
    * Elven Lords (1987)
    * Gamesmen of Kasar (1982)
    * Goblin Lake (1979)
    * Hela's House of Dark Delights (1982)
    * Labyrinth (1977)
    * Mistywood (1981)
    * Naked Doom (1977)
    * New Sorcerer Solitaire (1993)
    * Old Sorcerer Solitaire (1979)
    * Overkill (1977)
    * Red Circle (1987)
    * Sea of Mystery (1981)
    * Sewers of Oblivion (1980)
    * Solo for the Intellectually Challenged (1993)
    * Sword for Hire (1979)
    * Trollstone Caverns (1979)
    * Weirdworld (1977)
    * When the Cat's Away (1993)

The basis for this conversion is the Corgi edition of the T&T 5th
Edition rules, although the Flying Buffalo editions have also been
consulted. Some special combats, item powers, abilities, and spells are
not currently implemented.
  Amiga: The game provides a ReAction GUI for OS3.5+ users and
illustrations for OS3.0+ users. It can also be run as a console
application instead (eg. for use as a BBS door game, or for OS2.0-3.1
users).
@endnode

@node Requ "System Requirements"

@{b}SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS-------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

These are for the AmigaOS 2.0+ version of T&T:

@{b}Hardware@{ub}         Required        about 8Mb free RAM
                 Recommended     800*600 or larger Workbench
@{b}Firmware@{ub}         Required        Kickstart 2.0+
                 Recommended     Kickstart 3.1
@{b}Software@{ub}         Required        AmigaOS 2.0+
                 Recommended     AmigaOS 3.5+

Amiga: OS3.5+ users will get the proper ReAction GUI. OS2.0-3.1 users will
use a console-based interface for input and output. OS3.0+ users who have
graphics enabled will get illustrations, but you will need to have a GIF
datatype (eg. http://aminet.net/util/dtype/GIFdatatype-39.lha ) installed.
  If running on MorphOS, or if texteditor.gadget can't be opened, the
console window will be used for output instead.
  MorphOS: To run with the GUI, you need the appropriate ClassAct/ReAction
classes (eg. window.class, etc.) installed. You can get these classes at
http://amigan.1emu.net/releases/RA-MOS.lha . Those files are sourced from
AmigaOS 3.9+BB2, except that window.class V42.84 is provided instead of
V45.16. This is because MorphOS is incompatible with window.class 45.16:
opening it will cause a hang. Simply copy these ReAction classes into
SYS:Classes/ . Although they are compiled for 68020, they will work under
MorphOS.
  The Windows version requires Windows NT4 or later (ie. Windows NT/2000/
XP/Vista/7/8/8.1/10).
  If you don't like the illustrations, you can delete the images/
directory (and all subdirectories thereof).
  Windows XP+: If you are using the "log to console" option and are getting
the wrong glyphs in the output (aka console) window (eg. for the "half" (½)
symbol), click the system menu of the console window, choose the "Properties"
menu item, choose the "Font" tab, choose something @{i}other@{ui} than
"Raster Fonts" (eg. "Consolas"), then click "OK". If asked, choose "Save
properties for future windows with same title" and click "OK".
@endnode

@node Usag "Usage"

@{b}USAGE---------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

@{b}CLI Arguments@{ub}

                                    @{b}TnT@{ub}

@{b}Format:    TnT@{ub} [PUBSCREEN <screen>] [USERID <userid>]
           [[FILE] <filename>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}  PUBSCREEN/K, (Amiga only)
           USERID/K,    (Amiga only)
           FILE

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}   An implementation of the Tunnels and Trolls RPG.

@{b}Specification:@{ub}

    PUBSCREEN (Amiga only):
               the name of the public screen to run on.

    USERID (Amiga only):
               a string of up to 40 characters, representing a user's
               account on a BBS. Providing this will put the game into
               @{"BBS door mode" link Play}.

    FILE:      the name of a character to load at startup.

Windows version:
  We recommend that you install the provided TopazPlus.fon font (by
double-clicking it, then clicking the "Install" button). This will make
the ANSI artwork look as intended.
  You should ensure that the current directory is the
one in which the executable (TNT.EXE) resides, when you launch the
emulator (since Windows doesn't appear to have any equivalent to
PROGDIR:). This will ensure that all features which rely on external
files (eg. illustrations) work correctly.
@endnode

@node Cred "Credits and Licence"

@{b}CREDITS AND LICENCE-------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

@{b}Credits@{ub}

This implementation of Tunnels & Trolls was designed and programmed by
James Jacobs of Amigan Software. The BBS door graphics were drawn by
Daniel Kelly. The Topaz+1200 font was designed by dMG of t!s .
  The game itself was designed by Ken St. Andre. The included
adventures were written by various people, and illustrated by Josh Kirby
(Corgi) and various other people (Flying Buffalo). The game and adventures
were mostly published by Flying Buffalo (all except HH) and Corgi Books
(AK/AS/BF/BS/CD/CT/DE/GK/MS/MW/ND/RB/SH/TC). This conversion is
unofficial. We suggest buying something from Flying Buffalo to show your
