@node Play "How to Play"

@{b}HOW TO PLAY---------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

@{b}Guild@{ub}

To leave the guild, you need a character. "Generate" will create a new,
first-level character. "Autogenerate" will allow you to choose from a
roster of pre-made characters. "Import" lets you use an existing character
from the official "Tunnels and Trolls: Crusaders of Khazan" game (that
game is only available for MS-DOS; however, both the IBM-PC and Amiga
versions of this implementation can import these characters). You can
also, of course, "Load" a character you have previously saved.
  If you have a favourite "real" character (eg. your character from a
real-life T&T campaign) that you want to use, choose "Generate". Then
after creating a character, choose "Edit". You will then be able to
change the statistics of the character as necessary.

@{b}Options@{ub}

There are various options which can be accessed with the "O" command. They
are mostly self-explanatory.

Print text: While playing a module, this option will print out all the
paragraphs of the module, and descriptions for any wandering monsters and/
or treasure in the module.
  When not playing a module (eg. while in the city), this option will print
out all the descriptions of weapons, armour, spells and races.
  In any case, this output is not shown in the output gadget, but only in
the console window (and logfile, if any).

Colours: Note that this setting is ignored by the Amiga and thus will only
have an effect under Windows (and even then, only in the console window).

Graphics: Controls the amount of graphics shown.
  "All" graphics: Show room, weapon and incidental illustrations.
(Incidental illustrations are a group of illustrations not belonging to
any particular room. If a room doesn't have its own illustration, a random
incidental illustration will be shown instead.)
  "Some" graphics: Show room and weapon illustrations only.
  "None" graphics: Don't show any illustrations.

Cheat mode: When this is active, enemies will not be able to generate any
hits against you, and you will automatically make any saving roll.
   Sudden death situations (eg. as dictated by a module) are still possible.
Other cheats such as encumbrance, weapon requirements, etc. are controlled
by separate options.

Show unimplemented text: If this is on, unimplemented text (ie. rules
which are currently ignored) is shown in dark cyan. If this is off,
unimplemented text is never shown to the user at all.

Screen height: If this is nonzero, you will be prompted to press ENTER
after each screenful of text is shown. It only has effect in non-GUI mode
(ie. BBS door mode or OS2.0-3.1 mode).

Word wrapping: This setting is ignored for the GUI (it always does its own
word wrapping); it only affects non-GUI output. 0 will disable it.

Show instructions: If this is off, text from the module that deals with
how to run the module yourself in a pen-and-paper scenario (and thus is of
dubious relevance when playing on the computer) is not shown.

Adjust city selling prices: This controls how much the shop will pay
you when you sell standard items to them. Standard items are those that
can be bought at the shop. The shop will always pay full price for non-
standard items.
  This applies to the city shop, and also the anteroom shops in the Arena
of Khazan, Beyond the Silvered Pane and Deathtrap Equalizer.

Minimum saving roll: The 5th Edition rules stipulate that the
minimum throw for a saving roll is 5. Hence, 1 in 9 times, on average,
even the easiest possible saving roll will be failed.
  However, for Deluxe T&T Edition, the minimum throw is 4 (meaning that
only 1 in 18 easy rolls will fail), which arguably improves the fairness
and playability.
  Setting it to 3 is a cheat because it means that all saving rolls will
succeed automatically (as doubles add on and roll over).

@{b}City@{ub}

You can go in the "Arena" for combat practice, if desired. (Note that this
is not the Arena of Khazan.) This uses the monster tables from the
rulebook to create random encounters. There are also various shops, a
bank, etc.
  If you are going on an adventure where you might lose all your
possessions, we suggest visiting the bank beforehand and depositing your
equipment and money there.
  The "Advance" option handles both level advancement and language
training.
  Waiting in the city will restore 1 ST per turn (10 minutes), and 1 CON
per day.

@{b}Spells@{ub}

When listing spells:

L means level, eg. L5 means a level 5 spell.

(O) represents a circle in the original rules.
  It means the spell may be employed as a higher level spell for greater
effect.

(A) represents a triangle in the original rules.
  It means that employing the spell at higher levels doubles the duration
of the spell for each level higher.

(OA) represents a circle and a triangle.
  Those spells which can be raised in time or effect cannot be raised in
both time and effect simultaneously. The spellcaster must specify which he
desires upon casting the spell.

See the rulebook (section 2.22) for more information.

@{b}Output@{ub}

Text that is surrounded by square brackets [], or in yellow, is
unimplemented; ie. you should ignore any such text.
  Text that is red denotes paragraph numbers.
  Text that is cyan denotes possible user input.
  Amiga: Pressing the Help key in the input (string) gadget will scroll
the output (texteditor) gadget down by one screenful, or back to the top
if already at the bottom.
  Windows: Pressing the cursor up or down (or PgUp or PgDn) keys in the
input (single-line edit) control will scroll the output (multi-line edit)
control up or down, as appropriate, by one screenful.

@{b}Adventures@{ub}

When there is a choice of paragraphs, type the number of the paragraph you
want and press ENTER.
  If there is only one choice available, you can just press ENTER. If you
turn patience off in the options, you won't even need to do this.
  Where a letter is enclosed in square brackets, eg. [G], this indicates
the default you will get by just hitting the ENTER key.
  You can drop items and coins with the "D" (drop) command, and then
subsequently retrieve them with the "G" (get) command. This is intended
for cases where eg. you cast a lot of spells during a combat, thus
depleting your strength, and have to drop some weapons for encumbrance
reasons. After the combat, you can pick them up again. If you move to
another paragraph, the items and coins (being unguarded) will disappear
(be stolen).
  The "Q" (quit) command, or clicking the close gadget of the sheet
window, will automatically save your character before quitting. For
Windows users, note that closing the console window (if any) will not save
the game (nor will it allow the game to shut itself down cleanly).
  In most cases where there are multiple choices available, you can ask
the computer to choose one randomly using the "R" (random) command. This
is useful when eg. you have already previously played some or all of the
module and don't want to give yourself an unfair advantage (as suggested
in the instructions for several modules, eg. Naked Doom).

@{b}Character sheet@{ub}

'A' is in the complete armour slot.
'B' is held in both hands (ie. a 2-handed item).
'C' is in the chest armour slot (eg. arming doublet).
'E' means you are holding one of these in each hand (ie. a 1-handed item).
'G' is the legs armour slot (eg. greaves).
'H' is in the head armour slot (eg. helmets).
'M' is in the arms armour slot (eg. gauntlets).
'L' is held in your left hand (only).
'R' is held in your right hand (only).
'U' means this item is equipped (in use, but not held in a hand).
'·' means "none of the above".

Most items are not equippable. Of course, you cannot combine complete
armour with partial (head, arm, torso, leg) armour, as per the T&T rule.
  To 'equip' (wield) a weapon or shield, use the "Right" or "Left" command
(as appropriate for which hand you want to use). To 'equip' (wear) armour,
use the "Armour" command. For other items, use the "Equip" command.
  When the items listbrowser is not ghosted, you can use an item by
clicking on it. Similarly, when the spells listbrowser is not ghosted, you
can cast a spell by clicking on it.
  Generally, you can play either via keyboard or mouse. The buttons
below the input gadget can be used to choose among the possible actions.
Entering a string (eg. your character's name after generating him),
number, module name or spell name requires use of the keyboard.
  Giving 'Q' as your input, at any time, will quit the game.

@{b}Editing@{ub}

You can also edit most aspects of your character, if necessary (via the
Options command). This allows you to eg. use a real character from a real
T&T campaign, or work around any bugs/incomplete aspects. Obviously it is
also useful for cheating ;-)
  Note that using the "edit location" (ie. teleport) functionality may
conceivably cause a crash in some circumstances, as certain paragraphs are
only intended to be reached via certain other paragraphs.

@{b}BBS door mode@{ub}

The Amiga version can be run on a BBS server to provide users with access
to the game. It differs from normal in these ways:

    * Each user has their own subdirectory in which their
      characters and configuration file are stored. The game won't let
      users play with another user's character.
    * All input and output is via the console (CLI).
    * The character sheet and illustrations window are never opened.
    * ANSI escape sequences are used to provide coloured text, if the user
      has coloured text enabled in the options.
    * Some screens, eg. guild and city, are replaced with fancy ANSI
      versions.

This program is only required for hosting a T&T game (ie. if you run your
own BBS), not for merely playing one.
  If you run it from a normal Amiga CLI, the output will look garbled. It
is intended to run in conjunction with the appropriate BBS door hosting
software.

Notes for players:
  If playing on eg. an IBM-PC, you will need to configure your telnet client
to just send LFs rather than CR+LF. Start Telnet (via eg. "telnet" at the
command line), and then issue this command (on Windows 8.1):

    clear crlf

For Microfilth Telnet on earlier versions of Windows, the command is:

    toggle crlf

This should only need to be done once ever. In future, you can access the
game just by typing (from the command prompt):

    telnet absinthebbs.net 1940

(or whatever BBS you want to use.)
  Note that Telnet is disabled by default in recent versions of Windows.
You will need to enable it (or use a third-party telnet client). See eg.
https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/910.windows-7-enabling-telnet-client.aspx
  Windows: If your telnet client supports different fonts, we recommend
you use the Topaz+1200.fon font (included in the Windows archive).
  Your terminal should be 80 columns wide, otherwise some of the artwork
will not display correctly. The artwork is designed to ideally be viewed
in the Topaz+ 1200 font. The Amiga version of this font is provided in the
Amiga archive. You should configure your telnet client to use this font.
  There are T&T games running at the Absinthe BBS (telnet to
absinthebbs.net port 1940) and Reign of Fire BBS (telnet to
rofbbs.ddns.net port 2300).
@endnode

@node Rule "Rulebook"

@{b}RULEBOOK------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

(Note: This is the short version of the rules, as found at the start of the
Corgi solos. The complete (long version) rulebook can be downloaded from
http://amigan.1emu.net/releases/rulebook.rar . Additionally, some race
descriptions and spells used in this program are sourced from Monsters!
Monsters! (4th Edition).)

The Tunnels & Trolls solitaire games provide the means for you to play the
part of an adventurous hero in mystical, magical times. Such an adventurer
seeks wealth, fame and glory in ancient citadels filled with monsters and
treasures galore. To play this game, you will need some rough paper, a
pencil or pen, and a number of six-sided dice (at least three). You might
find index cards useful, and there may be occasions where you are asked to
use an ordinary deck of cards.

CREATING YOUR ADVENTURER
  Each adventurer is defined by "Prime Attributes": Strength,
Intelligence, Luck, Constitution, Dexterity, Charisma and Speed. They
define the character's basic innate abilities. Other details, like the
character's name, sex, hair and eye colour, kindred and character type,
round a character out, but the "Prime Attributes" are the factors that
make the game work.
  Roll three six-sided dice, add up the scores and write them next to the
prime attributes: use pencil becaquse these numbers could change later.
Repeat the roll for each attribute listed.
  STRENGTH (ST) is the ability to exert force - lifting, shoving, etc.
Strength limits your choice of weapons and tells you how much you can
carry. If ST ever falls to 0 or below your character is dead.
  INTELLIGENCE (IQ) measures a character's ability to reason, solve
problems, and remember.
  LUCK (LK) measures how blind chance works for or against your character.
Luck affects combat results, and is usually the attribute affecting
"Saving Rolls" (explained in its own section).
  CONSTITUTION (CON) measures a character's health. Combat damage is
subtracted from Constitution. If CON reaches 0, the character is dead.
  DEXTERITY (DEX) refers to both manual dexterity and physical agility.
Marksmanship is defined by Dexterity.
  CHARISMA (CHR) measures personal attractiveness and leadership ability.
It is not just a measure of good looks, but most often it is treated as
such.
  SPEED (SPD) is how fleet of foot and how responsive a character is.
Speed is the only thing standing between many adventurers and the monsters
pursuing them.
  WEIGHT POSSIBLE is 100 times Strength. It measures how many "weight
units" a character can haul around. (If Mantaro the Inimitable has a ST of
15, he can carry 1500 weight units.) Ten weight units weigh one pound.

CHARACTER RACES
  The next thing you'll want to decide is whether or not you want your
character to be a human or to be one of the other ancient races which
inhabit this magical world. It is recommended that you start out with a
human, but especially in some of the more difficult adventures, you may
want to create a character from one of the tougher kindreds until you
develop a more experienced human.

DWARVES     ST and CON Î 2.
            CHR Î 2/3.
            All other attributes Î 1.
ELVES       IQ and DEX Î 2 (abridged) or Î 3/2 (rulebook)
            CHR Î 2.
            CON Î 2/3.
            All other attributes Î 1.
FAIRIES     ST and CON Î ¼.
            LK and DEX Î 3/2.
            CHR Î 2.
            IQ normal.
            Fairies, as could be expected, can fly - there's nothing more
            useless than a walking fairy. That is unless you want him to
            carry as much as possible - any fairy loaded to 0.1# more than
            half its carrying capacity is too overburdened to fly.
HOBBITS     ST Î ½.
            CON Î 2.
            DEX Î 3/2.
            All others Î 1.
HUMAN       Normal.
            All Prime Attributes Î 1.
LEPRECHAUNS ST Î ¼.
            DEX, IQ and LK Î 3/2.
            All others Î 1.
            All Leprechauns should be classed as wizards. Leprechauns are
            inherently magical, however, and it is part of their genetic
            heritage to be able to perform a spell akin to the Wink-Wing
            for a strength cost of only 5. However, there are no wizards'
            schools in the land of the Leprechauns (and they encourage
            none), so Leprechauns must purchase all other spells they wish
            to learn, just as a rogue is compelled to (the Wizards' Guild
            won't teach Leprechauns because the Leprechaun lords won't
            allow the Guild to open branch offices in their area...).
TROLLS      ST and CON Î 3.
            Other attributes Î 1.
            Trolls are monsters, and although some "good" trolls can be
            found, they are not always acceptable.

¼ = 1/4
½ = 1/2

As you can see, no single race is unconditionally better than any other
race. Humans are often the best all-round choice, and there is never any
question about whether they are the kind of adventurer accepted into a
scenario.

CHARACTER TYPES
  The final decision needed to create your character is what kind of
background and training he or she has had. This background determines how
the character makes a living and a great deal more. A character must fall
within one of the two categories listed below. Each category ha advantages
and disadvantages, strengths and weaknesses. Read through them all, and
then decide. (A recommendation: if this is the first time you have played
T&T, try a human warrior to begin with.)
  WARRIOR: A warrior understands force first, subtlety last. Warriors are
trained in using weapons and armour to their best advantage, and get twice
the normal listed protection from armour and shields they use. While
warriors can use most magical artifacts they find, warriors cannot cast
any magic (like being colour-blind, it is simply beyond their abilities).
If a character's ST is greater than his IQ or LK, that character could
make a good warrior.
  WIZARDS: Wizards (also called magicians, mages, magic-users and
sorcerers) are those individuals that had the innate ability and received
the training to control the psi-forces that power the arcane world of
magic. Only youngsters with a reasonably good Intelligence (IQ of 10 or
better) and decent Dexterity (DEX of 8 or better) will be trained by the
elder wizards of the all-pervasive Wizard's Guild. All the Level 1 spells
(detailed later) are the basic heritage of wizard characters. Spells
beyond that level must be purchased from the Wizard's Guild or discovered
while adventuring. Wizards can use a magic staff to reserve their energies
while casting magic.
  Because wizards spent their youth learning magic, they are inept at
using weapons. Only small weapons like daggers, and appropriate weapons
like quarterstaves may be used by wizards. Wizards do get combat adds, the
same as any other character type, and may wear what armour they choose
although they get only the armour's listed value in protection. If IQ is
greater than either ST or LK, the character could make a good wizard.
Don't forget a wizard must have an IQ of 10 or more, and a DEX of 8 or
more to begin with.
  ROGUES: Rogues are characters who have psi-ability to use magic, but for
one reason or another never received the training for it. Their IQ may
have been too low for acceptance by the Wizard's Guild; they may have been
street urchins without sufficient capital to pay the entrance fees; they
may have been brought up in a backwater village to small to bother with
such things; they may have been a high lord's younger child too lazy to
stick to the intense studies of either weapons or magic.
  Rogues have the ability to use any weapons of their choice (which they
have the attributes sufficient to be able to handle) as well as the
ability to learn magic from anyone they can find who will teach them how.
However, rogues will never find weapons and armour to serve them quite as
well as they do warriors (rogues do not get the "double" effect of armour)
and rogues must learn all their spells from a wizard.
  The Wizard's Guild will never teach them, for any fee. Rogues should
only be taught spells by the wizards of another player who, by rights,
should charge all the market will bear, as he has fees to pay out to the
Wizard's Guild to learn his higher level spells himself. (Of course, if a
rogue comes upon a means of learning spells while in a dungeon, this is
completely fair.)
  In learning spells, the rogue learns the individual skills necessary,
but will never have magic become second nature - thus no rogue can invent
new spells. Furthermore, the use of magic staffs by rogues is impossible,
as their utilization requires more understanding of the nature of magic
than any rogue will ever obtain.
  Also, rogues must cast spells at the full listed strength cost, even if
the rogue advances in levels. If a rogue casts a given spell at a higher
level, he must pay the full maximum ST cost. In addition, any magic above
7th level magic becomes as confusing to a rogue as to any warrior,
although the rogue himself can continue to use magic whether he himself is
5th level or 50th. Magic isn't easy, nor is it an art for the dilettante,
and these are the penalties rogues pay for lack of training.
  Rogues are modelled on Fritz Leiber's Gray Mouser of Jack Vance's Cugel
the Clever. Both magic and weapons serve them, but they live best by their
wit and luck. Due to some of the changes outlined above, rogues can now
advance to any level they can attain; they no longer must choose between
the vocation of warrior or mage after they've reached 7th level. For them
there is no advancement to the class of warrior-wizard; once a rogue,
always a rogue. It's a matter of training - or lack of it.
  WARRIOR-WIZARD: Warrior-wizards are a rare breed indeed. These are
characters to whom a moderate amount of magic training and weapons
training were both available in their growing years. It takes an uncommon
character to be able to absorb both, and good circumstance to be in the
right place at the right time to receive the training.
  A young warrior-wizard must have, above all else, better than average
attributes: all Prime Attributes (ST, IQ, LK, CON, DEX and CHR) except
SPD must be at least 12 when they are initially rolled up. (This is before
alterations are made in attributes for the humanoid kindred - on average,
there are no more elvish warrior-wizards than human ones.)
  A character cannot choose to be a warrior-wizard. He or she must be
"born" that way. You can choose to be a warrior, a wizard, or a rogue, but
never a warrior-wizard - circumstances of birth and training required to
create one are rare, and should be so in your games. (For the curious, the
odds are that only 1 in 360 characters will be a warrior-wizard.)
  The warrior-wizard has enough understanding of magic to use a staff
(deluxe or ordinaire) as a tool to aid concentration, but does not learn
as much from repetition as does a wizard. A warrior-wizard may subtract 1
from required Strength for every two levels he is above the level of spell
he is trying to cast. (Example: Aric Fairhair is a 5th level warrior-
wizard. If he is casting a 4th level spell, he has to pay normal Strength
cost for it, although if he has a staff it will take off Strength cost as
a 5th level staff (5 ST points). If he casts a 3rd level spell, he may
subtract 1 more ST point for proficiency; if he casts a 1st level spell,
he may subtract 2.)
  However, the invention of new spells will remain out of reach even for
these extraordinary people. A newly-created warrior-wizard comes equipped
with all 1st level spells, but thereafter he or she must buy them as a
rogue does - the Wizards' Guild will not teach warrior-wizards, either.
  On the subject of weapons and armour training, the warrior-wizard has
partial knowledge of what warriors are fully trained in - efficient use of
armour. Thus, warrior-wizards may add +1 to the effectiveness of any full
set of armour and/or any shield they use.
  Warrior-wizards are what rogues tended to evolve into, under the old
rules of T&T, in spite of the admonition to become wholly a warrior or
wholly a wizard. The common question was "why should a rogue forget how to
use weapons if he becomes a wizard, or forfeit all the magic learned if
the decision was to become a warrior?"
  This indeed seemed a fair question. For this reason we have placed some
additional limits on rogues (while allowing them to continue to climb in
levels), and added the class of warrior-wizards (but made them hard to
acquire). Were they common, the warrior-wizards could outclass everyone
around them - so the dice will have to be kind to you before you can add
one to your stable!

PROVISIONS AND EQUIPMENT
  You have determined virtually everthing about your character. Now it is
time to buy the provisions and equipment the character will need on his or
her adventures.
  Characters probably have a few possessions before that first big
adventure, but nothing really suitable for a serious adventurer. A
character scrapes up all the money possible and starts from scratch. To
determine the number of gold coins your character starts out with, roll 3
dice and multiply the result by 10 (you will get between 30 and 180 gold
pieces, abbreviated g.p.). Some things in the equipment lists you will not
be able to purchase immediately, but even after one adventure, the
character may be able to purchase more and better equipment with the
rewards of success.
  The basic unit of exchange is the gold piece, a simple gold coin. Prices
are all listed in gold pieces. There are also silver and copper coins. One
gold piece = 10 silver pieces (s.p.) = 100 copper pieces (c.p.). Every
coin, regardless of value, weighs 1 weight unit. This makes the basic unit
of weight also equal to a gold piece. Most jewels weigh no more than
1 g.p. (and most less), although large objects like jade statues have no
standard weight.
  All weapons have ST and DEX requirements. A character must meet these
required minimums to use the weapon. The "Weight" of a weapon is given in
weight units - remember Weight Carried. Keep track of the weight of
purchases and the weight of any money the character carries.
  The column of "Dice + Adds" pertains to the weapon's combat
effectiveness. The greater the numbers in these categories, the more
deadly the weapon is. Specifics are discussed under "Conducting Combat".
Wizards may not use weapons with more than 2 dice (but any number of adds)
in the Dice + Adds column.
  The column labelled "Range" states the maximum range for the weapon in
missile combat. If there is no listing, the weapon may not be used as a
missile. Further discussion of missile combat follows.
  An asterisk (*) indicates a weapon that requires two hands for proper
use. No second weapon or shield may be used unless the character has more
than two hands. Two weapons without asterisks may be used simultaneously
IF the user has the ST and DEX requirements for BOTH weapons (eg. to fight
with a dirk in each hand requires a minimum ST of 2 and a DEX of 8).

